Help! 16GB but can't find files! There are two /Recordings folders, one on the phone's memory, one on the external SD card - when checking those with a file browser, both folders contain no files - yet android says the recorder takes up 16GB! I want to put the files on a laptop and delete the app - how if they can't be found? EDIT: The folder on SD is empty. No mp3 files on the whole card, nor on the phone.
replyContent: Hi, considering that Hi-Q takes up 16GB, it means that your recordings are stored in app-private folder on your SD card. Go to your SD card, navigate to Android - data - com.hiqrecorder.full - files - Recordings, and you should be able to find your recording files there. Please email help@hiqrecorder.com for further help.

First, as a software engineer (30 years +), I am greatly  surprised how inexpensive smart phone apps have become. I doubt many people understand the complexities involved in software development.  Many thanks to the developers of this audio recorder.  Next, I make bamboo and cane flutes and use another app to tune them.  Of course I need a library of flute sounds  of my very own hand made flutes, therefore all of my recordings are only several minutes long, unless I start rambling about its construction...  So far, this app serves my purposes very well, and I  strongly recommend it for this use.  I cannot provide info about lengthy recordings or lecture recordings, but for my current needs, this app truly excels.  Finally, can anybody recommend an audio spectrum  analysis app so I can evaluate the frequency components  of each flute?  I suspect my ears are probably adequate, but I would like to find cause and effect between flute construction methods and the resulting sounds.  Many thanks in advance and as usual... THanks for THinking!  North Central Florida.

Tried it, looks cool. Yet to be tested in the field. I want to use it for taping concerts and conversations.  Some things could be better: 1. No monitoring to set the levels. 2. No automatic clipping control (really needed for concerts). 3. Mic selection doesn't specify the difference between Raw and Unprocessed. 4. No quick switch to select the mic (see below). 5. Gain control could have better UI. 6. No option to set the gain automatically to avoid clipping or low volume. 7. (if possible) 24-bit wav file output for easier post-processing. 8. No android quick actions - adding a shortcut to start recording immediately. Widgets don't count (can't add them to Oneplus toolbox). "Start recording automatically" option doesn't count either, sometimes I just want to start the app without recording.  I found 2 mic sources for the best quality: 1. Raw Audio seems to clip easily and is somewhat distorted, but better than other sources. Needs gain reduction for even ordinary volume situations. Useful for voice recording. 2. Unprocessed is too low-volume and gain does almost nothing with it. Could be good in high-volume concerts. A quick switch for these 2 (or presets maybe?) would be great.

I found something that I didn't like much because when I try to record 
something from YouTube or from other music apps there is a way in which the 
bar NOTIFICATION appears a record bottom and you press it but it actually 
throws you to the App UI of HQ recorder. You'll press the record button and 
then go back to YouTube or the other app you want to play music or audios, 
and it takes like 5 Seconds of wasted recording to go back from the 
Recorder HQ app to the other app and it takes a lot of time , and I feel 
like it should be just pressed in the notification bars and star recording 
(not opening the app) and nothing else. Just star Recording.
replyContent: There is a way to disable opening the app after you pause/stop the recording from the notification. Go to Hi-Q settings - Troubleshooting - Experimental features. Enter 447673 and tap OK. Press back twice. Go to Hi-Q settings - Experimental - Debug switches - UNTICK "open activity from recording notification" (might be already unticked), tap OK.

replyContent: Hi Roberto, we have received your email and have responded to it. The USB mic is not natively supported (it requires entirely different code to read the signal), but if the phone supports USB mic and treats it as a normal mic, it should work. As to why it crashes, we are trying to figure it out. Please try beta ver which has more reporting tool.

Many recording apps that I've tried didn't have as many options and therefore the recordings ended up to be too large to send in an email. However I was able to use a recording option on this app that allowed me to record myself talking for almost 15 minutes and then I was able to email that recording to my significant other, who is currently overseas in the United States Marine Corps. She had not heard my voice for over 8 months. But now we use this app to send voice recordings to each other as often as possible.   This app is very important to me and I give this app a 5 star rating and I have recommended this app to several people both in-and-out of the military.
